oriser" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="es-EnglishNS_en_20180322142639"/><CodeA name="es_score" value="100"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="2"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="glife"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Living/Lifestyle</CodeD><CodeI org="rbc" action="add"><CodeA name="rule" value="847446"/><CodeA name="db" value="prbc---00018592-20180327-145232"/></CodeI><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gweb"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="1"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="gcat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Political/General News</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gfake"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gweb"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:glife"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI><CodeI org="hierarchy" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00001004-20180327-161428"/><CodeA name="nodelevel" value="0"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Life</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Commentary; Stop, think before posting</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>To fight fake news and online hoaxes, first look at multiple sources and draw your own conclusion before sharing</Para><Para>With the revelation of Cambridge Analytica manipulating American voters' behaviour using Facebook, I assumed that people will be more careful in believing what they read on social media.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Instead, last week, I saw some friends on Facebook re-posting a well-known hoax. In this hoax, users are supposed to check if their Facebook accounts are being hacked by simply typing BFF in the comments section or their own post. If the BFF you type turns out to be green, you are safe. If not, you are supposed to be hacked and need to change your password.</Para><Para>And I saw a lot of green BFF being typed. Hooray, you are safe. Sorry, not really.</Para><Para>This is a Facebook feature called Text Delight. Try typing congratulations or best wishes on Facebook and you will see both being coloured differently.</Para><Para>So, you still don't know if your account is hacked. But you do look gullible.</Para><Para>The good thing about this hoax is that it is rather harmless, in the sense your profile is not going to be harvested and you are not being subconsciously manipulated.</Para><Para>However, the fact that most fake news, hoaxes and scams can proliferate so quickly is down to the users.</Para><Para>A study released this month by Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers showed that true news stories in social media platform Twitter took six times longer to reach 1,500 people, compared with fake news stories.</Para><Para>The study could not pinpoint the cause, but the researchers offered a data-backed speculation - fake news was more novel and more surprising than true news. Thus, human beings are more likely to retweet fake news than true news.</Para><Para>I personally think this whole fake news fiasco boils down to human nature. I feel that human beings are more likely to believe in news that ties in with their world views and beliefs, regardless of the truth.</Para><Para>It is like if you hate your incompetent boss, you tend to believe in gossip that he might have reached his current position by unscrupulous means.</Para><Para>Or if you think a particular newspaper is biased against a political party you support, you will not believe a word it prints.</Para><Para>So, how do you prevent fake news and other online hoaxes from spreading? I offer a simple solution.</Para><Para>Verify the news, look at multiple sources and draw your own conclusion before spreading the news.</Para><Para>If you come across juicy news, search the Internet and click on various results to see if it is true.</Para><Para>For example, a simple search of "Facebook BFF" would have elicited results that confirmed it is a hoax.</Para><Para>This is not rocket science. All you need to do is to resist clicking on the share button or copy-and-paste link, calm yourself for a few seconds, check various sources before deciding to share the news. If you are not sure, don't share it.</Para><Para>Do so, even if it may be news that align with your beliefs. Because sharing fake news that align with your beliefs only helps to undermine your beliefs, not promote them.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">Trevor Tan </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">(c) 2018 Singapore Press Holdings Limited </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

